Exploratory Data Analysis

  • Which types of crimes were most prevalent in 2023? In 2022?
  • How many crimes occured in the past year? In the past 5 years?
  • Which districts have the most occuring crimes?
crime_data %>% group_by(primary_type) %>%
  summarize(counts = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(primary_type, -counts),
             y = counts/sum(counts))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="royalblue") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent) +
  geom_text(aes(label=scales::percent(counts/sum(counts)), y = counts/sum(counts)),
            vjust = -0.5, size=3) +
  labs(
    title = "Frequency of Primary Crime Type",
    x = "",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))

crime_data %>%
  filter(year == 2023) %>%
  group_by(primary_type) %>%
  summarize(counts = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(counts)) %>%
  mutate(rank = row_number()) %>%
  filter(rank <= 10) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(primary_type, -counts),
             y = counts / sum(counts))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "royalblue") +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(counts / sum(counts)), y = counts / sum(counts)),
            vjust = -0.5, size = 3, color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Top 10 Most Frequent Crimes in 2023",
    x = "Primary Crime Type",
    y = "Relative Frequency"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

crime_data %>%
  filter(year == 2022) %>%
  group_by(primary_type) %>%
  summarize(counts = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(counts)) %>%
  mutate(rank = row_number()) %>%
  filter(rank <= 10) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(primary_type, -counts),
             y = counts / sum(counts))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "indianred") +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(counts / sum(counts)), y = counts / sum(counts)),
            vjust = -0.5, size = 3, color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Top 10 Most Frequent Crimes in 2022",
    x = "Primary Crime Type",
    y = "Relative Frequency"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

crime_data$date = as.Date(crime_data$date)

crime_data %>%
  filter(year == 2023) %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(crime_count = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = crime_count, color = factor(month(date)))) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(
    "1" = "royalblue",  # January
    "2" = "royalblue",  # February
    "3" = "royalblue",  # March
    "4" = "royalblue",  # April
    "5" = "royalblue",  # May
    "6" = "royalblue",  # June
    "7" = "royalblue",  # July
    "8" = "royalblue",  # August
    "9" = "red",        # September (change color to red)
    "10" = "royalblue", # October
    "11" = "royalblue", # November
    "12" = "royalblue"  # December
  )) +
  labs(
    title = "Number of Crimes in 2023",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Number of Crimes"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  guides(color=F)

The number of crimes is most frequent in the month of September.

crime_data %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(crime_count = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = crime_count)) +
  geom_line(color = "royalblue") +
  labs(
    x = "Date",
    y = "Number of Crimes"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

crime_data %>%
  group_by(year, district) %>%
  summarize(crime_count = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(district, -crime_count), y = crime_count)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "royalblue") +
  geom_text(aes(label = crime_count, y = crime_count),
            vjust = -0.5, size = 3, color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Number of Crimes by District",
    x = "District",
    y = "Number of Crimes"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  facet_wrap(~year, scales = "free_x", ncol = 2)

## `.groups` argument.

Spatial-temporal analysis in R

library(sp)
## Warning: package 'sp' was built under R version 4.3.2
crime_df = crime_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(longitude) & !is.na(latitude))

# Create a SpatialPointsDataFrame
coordinates(crime_df) <- c("longitude", "latitude")
proj4string(crime_df) <- CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84")

# Plot using the sp library
sp::plot(crime_df, pch = 3, col = "black", main = "Longitude vs. Latitude",
     xlab = "Longitude", ylab = "Latitude")

library(sp)
library(spacetime)
## Warning: package 'spacetime' was built under R version 4.3.2
library(dplyr)

crime_df <- crime_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(longitude) & !is.na(latitude))

# Create a SpatialPointsDataFrame
crime_spdf <- SpatialPointsDataFrame(
  coords = crime_df[, c("longitude", "latitude")],
  data = crime_df,
  proj4string = CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84")
)

# Plot using the sp library
plot(crime_spdf, pch = 3, col = "black", main = "Longitude vs. Latitude",
     xlab = "Longitude", ylab = "Latitude")

# Create the spatio-temporal data frame
ChicagoCrime_years <- 2019:2023
ChicagoCrime_date <- as.Date(
  paste(ChicagoCrime_years, "-01-01", sep = ""),
  format = "%Y-%m-%d"
)

chicago_stdf <- STIDF(
  crime_spdf,
  data = data.frame(x = crime_spdf@data),
  time = as.POSIXct(ChicagoCrime_date)
)

# Print the resulting spatio-temporal data frame
print(chicago_stdf)
